 Redemption, Thomas G.W. Telfer analyses the ideas, interests, and institutions that shaped the evolution of Canadian bankruptcy law in this era. Examining the vigorous public debates over the idea of bankruptcy, Telfer argues that the law was shaped by conflict over the morality of release from debts and by the divergence of interests between local and distant creditors. Ruin and Redemption is the first full-length study of the origins of Canadian bankruptcy law, thus making it an important contribution to the study of Canada’s commercial law.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBankruptcyzCanada. 0aDebtor and creditorzCanada. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Business Law.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060681240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144261968540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442619685423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442619685.jpg  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK